  "prompt_text": "Implement a trie data structure. When is a trie more efficient than a hash table?",
  "response_text": "**Trie Implementation in Python**\n================================\n\nA trie, also known as a prefix tree, is a data structure that is often more efficient than a hash table in certain scenarios. It is particularly useful for tasks that involve prefix matching or autocompletion.\n\n```python\nclass TrieNode:\n    \"\"\"A node in the trie data structure.\"\"\"\n    \n    def __init__(self):\n        # Initialize an empty dictionary to store children and a boolean to mark the end of a word\n        self.children = {}\n        self.is_end_of_word = False\n\n\nclass Trie:\n    \"\"\"A trie data structure.\"\"\"\n    \n    def __init__(self):\n        # Initialize the root node\n        self.root = TrieNode()\n\n    def insert(self, word):\n        \"\"\"Insert a word into the trie.\"\"\"\n        \n        node = self.root\n        for char in word:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                # If the character is not in the children, create a new node\n                node.children[char] = TrieNode()\n            node = node.children[char]\n        # Mark the end of the word\n        node.is_end_of_word = True\n\n    def search(self, word):\n        \"\"\"Search for a word in the trie.\"\"\"\n        \n        node = self.root\n        for char in word:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                # If the character is not in the children, the word is not in the trie\n                return False\n            node = node.children[char]\n        # Check if the word is at the end of a branch\n        return node.is_end_of_word\n\n    def starts_with(self, prefix):\n        \"\"\"Check if there are any words that start with a given prefix.\"\"\"\n        \n        node = self.root\n        for char in prefix:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                # If the character is not in the children, there are no words with this prefix\n                return False\n            node = node.children[char]\n        # If we've reached this point, there are words with this prefix\n        return True\n\n    def autocomplete(self, prefix):\n        \"\"\"Get all words that start with a given prefix.\"\"\"\n        \n        node = self.root\n        for char in prefix:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                # If the character is not in the children, there are no words with this prefix\n                return []\n            node = node.children[char]\n        \n        # Perform a depth-first search to find all words that start with the prefix\n        return self._dfs(node, prefix)\n\n    def _dfs(self, node, prefix):\n        \"\"\"A helper function to perform a depth-first search.\"\"\"\n        \n        words = []\n        if node.is_end_of_word:\n            # If we've reached the end of a word, add it to the list\n            words.append(prefix)\n        for char, child_node in node.children.items():\n            # Recursively search the child nodes\n            words.extend(self._dfs(child_node, prefix + char))\n",
